  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2286855003" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2286855003" />
    <a title="Jo" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/12091097-jo"><img alt="Jo" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1346006680p2/12091097.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2286855003?book_show_action=true">Mar 01, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jo" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jo" href="/user/show/12091097-jo">Jo</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/11186691-the-bell">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2286855003" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10641873329236222089">3.5 stars<br/><br/>This is the fourth Iris Murdoch book for me in the readathon I’m participating in (<a target='_blank' rel='noopener nofollow' href='https://librofulltime.wordpress.com/the-great-iris-murdoch-readalong-november-2017-december-2019/'>https://librofulltime.wordpress.com/t...</a>) and I had high expectations after enjoying the first three. The Bell, however, was a tricky one for me and I believe it was largely due to the fact that there is a great deal of religious exposition and discussion in this book, lots of wringing of hands over sin and morality especially in regard to being gay and Christian.<br/><br/>The novel centers on a lay community in Gl</span>
  <span id="freeText10641873329236222089" style="display:none">3.5 stars<br /><br />This is the fourth Iris Murdoch book for me in the readathon I’m participating in (<a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://librofulltime.wordpress.com/the-great-iris-murdoch-readalong-november-2017-december-2019/">https://librofulltime.wordpress.com/t...</a>) and I had high expectations after enjoying the first three. The Bell, however, was a tricky one for me and I believe it was largely due to the fact that there is a great deal of religious exposition and discussion in this book, lots of wringing of hands over sin and morality especially in regard to being gay and Christian.<br /><br />The novel centers on a lay community in Gloucestershire, England which shares its grounds with an Abbey where the nuns are cloistered. There are about six original members of the community who are joined at the beginning of the story by Paul who is researching 14th century manuscripts and then his wife Dora and an 18 year old boy, Toby.<br /><br />Dora Greenfield is the first character we meet in the novel and is a young, careless if not carefree woman, who has left her possessive husband for a while and has now decided she will reconcile with him at the Abbey. Despite her whimsicality Dora is a complex character whose focus on the present moment has both positives and negatives for herself and those around her.<br /><br />In contrast to Dora is Catherine, a virginal young woman who is about to enter the Abbey as a nun and who Dora initially resents for purely superficial reasons as she compares herself physically to the younger woman. Dora also frets for Catherine and the idea that she won’t be able to leave the Abbey yet, Dora herself is similarly trapped with Paul, as she says <b>‘That was marriage, thought Dora; to be enclosed in the aims of another.’</b><br /><br />Toby is another young and carefree visitor to the community who provides some comic relief in his insistence of using his new word ‘rebarbative’ in an array of instances but whose innocence is challenged in his encounters with others. Innocence sullied and superficial, is part of the religious and moral aspects to the novel for there are several characters who are more than they appear, who are hiding something whether they wish to or not and this notion of secrets and suppressed and hidden identity has run through other Murdoch novels I have read recently.<br /><br />Dora and Toby find one another and embark upon a scheme involving the titular Bell which mirrors other 'Murdochian' plans with similar results. There is a cringe worthy quality to these ambitious plans that the reader feels cannot possibly succeed and an easing of tension when plans change. Dora and Toby seem similar, both immature and naïve but Toby’s naivety comes from innocence rather than ignorance and in contrast to his simple faith, Dora sees herself as a ‘priestess’ longing for attention and reverence from those around her.<br /><br />Michael is the other main character in the novel, a closeted and troubled gay man who is constantly measuring his desire for men against his religious faith. Iris Murdoch was aware of the homophobia of the time and I think, manages to make Michael sympathetic in his torture if his religious philosophizing and what A.S. Byatt calls his ‘spiritual masochism’, gets too much for this reader. I know from reading Liz Dexter's <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/36171781.Iris_Murdoch_and_the_Common_Reader" title="Iris Murdoch and the Common Reader by Liz Dexter" rel="nofollow noopener">Iris Murdoch and the Common Reader</a> that some readers believe Michael’s behavior verges on pedophilia however, this didn’t occur to me because of the way in which Murdoch writes about Nick, and the adult Nick himself is a conundrum, one of those characters that appear in Murdoch novels that are never really illuminated or explained. <br /><br />Other characters include James, Patches and Mrs. Mock and her husband with the first two standing in stark contrast to Michael and Dora, apparently straight shooters who find the world infinitely simple to understand while the latter two are also hiding something behind their religious convictions although we are never to know what that is.<br /><br />London appears as the antithesis to the community as a world where God is no longer important with Noel the journalist a strident atheist who despises the religious. It is where Dora can have freedom, looking at paintings in the National Gallery and calling them <b>‘something superior and good’</b>, a secular version of the nuns and the Abbey. The community, however, has its lure, both for her and the reader and I loved the idea of living off the land and how the grounds were laid out surrounded by the water, the secluded peace of the Abbey with its high walls and the way the weather and the time of day changed its aspect. The nuns make few appearances but their serenity and strength is communicated effectively as is their simple faith.<br /><br />Ultimately, this novel contains Murdoch’s wonderful writing, her ability to conjure up a place, characters that range in complexity and empathy and scenes of contemplation and action but the religious philosophizing and agonizing does harm the novel for someone who isn’t themselves religious, who found the sermons that James and Michael give tedious and distracting and as such I can’t rate this novel as highly as the three others I have read. As I have said before, however, I am still very much looking forward to my continuing journey through the work of this wonderful writer.<br /><br />Some choice lines;<br /><br /><b>“I’m afraid”, he said, “that Mrs. Greenfield is what is popularly called a bitch. I’m sorry to say so, but one must call things by their names. Only endless trouble comes from not doing so.”<br /><br /> ‘It was sunny again, but chill; the dusty illusions of late summer were giving place to the golden beauties of autumn, sharper and more poignantly ephemeral.’</b><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="10641873329236222089" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

