    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2316306039" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2316306039" />
    <a title="Daniela" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/62181206-daniela"><img alt="Daniela" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1527432849p2/62181206.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2316306039?book_show_action=true">Mar 16, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Daniela" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Daniela" href="/user/show/62181206-daniela">Daniela</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2316306039" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5511896549179771366"><br/>This was my first novel by Iris Murdoch and I think she gained an enthusiastic reader. <br/><br/>I am not entirely certain I can write a coherent review of this novel because, although the story is quite straightfoward, the inner workings of the book&apos;s themes are somehow a mystery to me. Murdoch&apos;s greatest strength lies in her ability to read her characters, to explain their thoughts and to explore their contradictions. Her characters come alive because they are incoherent, because they change their mind,</span>
  <span id="freeText5511896549179771366" style="display:none"><br />This was my first novel by Iris Murdoch and I think she gained an enthusiastic reader. <br /><br />I am not entirely certain I can write a coherent review of this novel because, although the story is quite straightfoward, the inner workings of the book's themes are somehow a mystery to me. Murdoch's greatest strength lies in her ability to read her characters, to explain their thoughts and to explore their contradictions. Her characters come alive because they are incoherent, because they change their mind, because they contain a wide array of feelings and sensations, forever torn between notions of right and wrong, heart and head. <br /><br />Many reviews of this novel here on Goodreads remark upon several aspects of it, far better than I ever could. For this reason, I chose to underline how the book plays with the notion of retreat from the world, and how it eventually tells us that it is a futile attempt. You can't hide or run away from your troubles, you can't simply believe that going away will fix everything, or that it will give you peace. I am not certain I completely agree with this - I have a great appreciation for the escape route. But I certainly enjoy how the story subtly tells us that eventually we have to face up to ourselves while also telling us to proceed in that path with gentleness and care. Love oneself as one loves others, and that love will prevail. </span>
  <a data-text-id="5511896549179771366" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


